   <title type="text">Newly Open Access Journal: The Akhenaten Sun</title>
   <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.theamarnaresearchfoundation.org/articles.html">The Akhenaten Sun</a><br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><img alt="http://www.theamarnaresearchfoundation.org/Images/header.jpg" height="93" src="http://www.theamarnaresearchfoundation.org/Images/header.jpg" width="320" /></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size: x-small;">The Amarna period of Egyptian history began during the reign of the  pharaoh Amenhotep III nearly 3,400 years ago. This was a period of  tremendous artistic and architectural achievement. The famous Colossi of  Memnon were built, wonderful additions were made to the temples at  Luxor and Karnak, and seeds were sown for a monotheistic religion.<br /><br />    Upon the death of Amenhotep III, his son Amenhotep IV became pharaon  of Egypt. This "heretic king" changed his name to Akhenaten, quickly  abandoned the pantheon of Egyptian gods and declared the sun-god, Aten,  to be the only god.  He and his queen, Nefertiti, built a new city,  known as Akhetaten (Horizon of the Aten) at the present site of Tell  el-Amarna.  From there he ruled all Egypt and directed the worship of  his one god, Aten.    <br />  <br /> Following the death of Akhenaten, Tutankhamun (who was born  Tutankh-aten, and is believed by a great many Egyptologists to have been  Akhenaten's son), returned the religious capital of Egypt to Thebes.  The monuments of the "heretic king" were destroyed and the memory of his  reign was erased. But the eighteen year reign of Akhenaten had touched  upon a religious philosophy and an artistic style that still echoes  today.<br /><br /> The Amarna Research Foundation is dedicated exclusively to the  advancement of interest and research in the this fascinating slice of  ancient history.&nbsp; </span></blockquote><div style="text-align: left;"><blockquote class="tr_bq"><a class="largetext" href="http://www.theamarnaresearchfoundation.org/Sun2015%20Spring%20Vol%2020%20No%202.pdf" ta